At Need for Speed: The Run competes all over America.
Review
A trip, in principle neglected, is complicated by a series of improper neglects of a routine journey during the morning shift.
To some extent expectations were met, but that is no use if, in fact, nothing extraordinary was intended to be done.
The new delivery, to which the title is added The Run, aroused great expectations already before its premiere.
I promised that I would give new air to the old race saga Need for Speed and, as shown, appears as a game that should not end up again being a genre of action without more.
We also feel curious about how the scenes would stay, where the main character descends from the car and walks by his own foot.
As often happens in the NFS series, the results do not vary much from what we expected.
There are careers that can be done for acceptable, but in the total calculation points are lost due to absurd failures, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In reality, they cannot be called errors, but rather, they are the incomprehensible detachment of programmers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced into a story, whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, you are offered to participate in an illegal career throughout America.
You sit at the wheel on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to get the first to New York.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
In this way, you don’t even have the feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasant to see, although the technical level of the graph is equivalent to that of previous deliveries of the series.
So it's nothing of the other world.
But the stroll through the desert, the autumn landscape or the high snow-covered mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, racing is now and again diversified by an atypical element.
For example, in the wilderness you find a sandstorm that diminishes visibility.
On the other hand, you must be careful not to bury an avalanche in the mountains.
According to that, each race is very well developed.
There's only a couple of models, but that's enough.
For a moment, you try to advance a number of required rivals (the normal in a classic race), then try to earn time (the classic timed duel) and then a duel awaits you against a single opponent.
In the middle of all this, sometimes the police appear, which only makes things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the button right at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are quite fewer landscapes in the game than could be expected (in particular there are only three).
But the final result is positive, because this element does not get upset and, in the context already mentioned, it is one of the elements that makes the game more interesting.
The driving model follows the tracks of previous episodes.
That means that today is no longer a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But a career designed with a lot of action is quite convenient for this driving style, although we can find something better among competition games.
So far, everything's in order.
But problems arise after a certain time.
Unlike the correct driving models, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
From games like this you can't expect to recreate deformations and complicated collisions, but in fact before a blow against any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so it's not all in order.
It is typical that, by making a very adjusted advance or circulating the car with a normal traffic, there are only slight pinks, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up doing uncontrolled pirouettes.
It's even completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, there are no major problems, but it can put you in a bad mood.
The resets are scheduled in such a way that, when you have an accident or get out of the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, in each race only five recipes are available.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something doesn't go well, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes, nor the reset helps, only helps to learn the given stage of memory.
A great disadvantage of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, you cannot take it.
Sometimes you will find yourself in some "civil" vehicle site always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth, or you arrive five minutes before or after.
This causes anger especially in situations, when you see two cars going to meet in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you must either turn around or stop.
It's the same when you get here, because it's programmed that the "surprise" will always happen in front of your nose.
The opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the game you will reach places where, regardless of the moment, you will always advance the same opponent on the same site.
This also happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at any price.
When it comes to you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars coming in front of you, so at first you can make the car roll.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspension and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it will surely disappoint you immediately.
And it's a shame, because even if the travel model is simple, the game is fun and with action, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn't matter, if merit takes the idea with fifty exclusive clues or the ranking in the race so that it doesn't break the boredom, or anything else.
An unusual idea is the change of cars during racing.
You have to be careful about the gas pumps next to the road, because that's exactly where you have to change cars, although in most cases what you have will be enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports are suitable for urban areas, U.S. strong cars for straight highways and super-deportable exotics for technical driving, for example by mountain roads with curves.
In addition, the main narrative thread also appears a thread of parallel challenges, that is, there are races in specific places that you will know about history.
Here you will get not only medals, but also points of experience for your profile, which serves both challenges and stories.
Upon reaching the upper level, the driver is opened up several possibilities, starting with the car and finishing with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an Autolog feature is connected online, which compares your results with those of other players and provides other community functions.
One of the most difficult elements to understand is how the last race is made in history.
With the car you reach the subway tunnel (passe), where you run dark through the tracks (passe).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (passe) and, suddenly, the metro convoy arrives behind you and takes you forward without more.
In writing we will probably have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game no one thought even a little or whether the authors actually take us for a bunch of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most pleasant cases, sometimes even superb.
For what a pity it is that, at the most tense times, the quality of the image is reduced and, sometimes, in a serious way.
This mainly affects accidents where many participants are involved, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to please most of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each one of his father and mother", but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for his music.
The final feeling of Need for Speed: The Run is therefore quite confused.
If the game avoids absolutely stupid mistakes, we would have trouble saying that The Run is the best NFS game in recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game is not over.
Fun is assured, but prepare because mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the force of some airport reflectors.
