History of IBM: from cheese cutter to space flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - it was originally a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis for the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "fix clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired his supervisory board until 1930.
Flint set the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM ( Watson's ideas remain the firm basis on which corporate culture and identity are underpinned).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all types of business appliances, from meat cutters and cheese to register boxes.
During the first four years of Watson's management of the company, billing doubled by $9 million and began the large expansion of the company across the continent.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years after occupying the chair of the chief, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (in Mercury, Saturn and 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer comprehensive advice and services of high value added.
The strategy that IBM has paid these last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet."
Its objective is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or the circumstances, for example, in the transport and management of cities have been improved.
For the trade sector, IBM recently presented the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
