How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime bent west and the journeys of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one was supposed to put himself in line with a sleeping bag and spend all night, or have "well known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for trips to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable agent", which thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their vacations in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses that the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of travelling the Czechs has suffered a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was not going to spend any more holidays in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, the visa exemption was imposed to travel to Western European neighbouring States, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups slept in parks in tents, since our income from then did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to carry with them food (preserved, stuffed, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also average wages, which led to an increase in travel demand around 1997.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began to regularly prepare trips using charter flight connections from 1997 onwards, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volumes.
By the end of the 90th century, the Czechs were already travelling visa-free to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czechia to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
From that year onwards, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have been flying away and hot. This winter will be flying directly from Czechia to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting around 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutional development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, so our country became among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent on trips abroad more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head, including expenses at the residence site.
