Walls have eyes: How researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivk was simply another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having killed in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of his time before his attack on his computer, talking to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to get on Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so difficult to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on European digital populism by the UK study centre DEMOS.
The flow of personal information on Facebook is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific precision - the way sellers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then they gave them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon reaching Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a completely new way of doing an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry about immigration.
However, in a sort of turn, "those who combine their activism online with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic jobs with the site name on the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study the people you could not approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very hard to identify them."
"You should go through the party, and they would never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that--you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno, University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues, found that university students who talked about their rubber feats on Facebook had a significantly greater risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counsellors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with their drunks.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Child Health, Behavior and Development Center at the Seattle Child Research Institute, Washington Post said.
"We've found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinking" its own population to get data.
The Site Data Team has developed statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the prospect of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom defenders have long claimed that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, liking them or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to undermine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, on a 2006 study that conducted with the public student Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know that part of a user's profile information and wall messages are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do out of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
That is why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a hat and a pen are still the best research tools no one can use.
"There is no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social - and a lot of social research is still going on offline."
