"I am a military commander in the Norwegian resistance movement and in the Temple Knights of Norway," he said in front of a room full of 500 people.
"I oppose the court, since it received the mandate of organizations that support the ideology of hate and because it supports multiculturalism."
"I recognize the facts, but I do not declare myself guilty."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during that monologue, because "he didn't want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this audience as a platform to express his views."
For the same reason he refused to allow Breivik, who had brought a written speech in advance, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered the police to keep Breivik in custody for another 12 weeks, banned access to the media for four weeks, and said the authorities would have to have strict control over all visits and correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 survivors and relatives of the victims attended the hearing.
Some came hoping to look at Breivik in the eyes, others to confirm that he was locked up.
They all attended with the aim of moving towards the conclusion.
"I thought it looked cold and inhuman," said a Utoya survivor to the Norwegian station NRK.
"It was uncomfortable, but for me it was a step forward after seeing and hearing the suspect."
Dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the audience and looked at journalists and survivors when he entered and left the building.
Despite Breivik's strange notion of being part of a larger "resistance" movement, the judge determined that he is not a mental illness, and said that there is no evidence that he acted with accomplices.
Some may be comforted that the July 22 attacks appear to be the work of an extremist instead of a group of radicals.
But that does not automatically soften the pain and confusion that a whole nation still feels.
"I'd like it to look like a monster, but it doesn't look like it," said a victim's relative.
"It would be much easier if it seemed."
7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview, are shown in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview with newly rediscovered Jobs that has been dusted out as advance of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the commercial processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a young man of flow diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawns of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At the time, Jobs had been forced to leave Apple for only 10 years, and he was already working intensively in his new NeXT computer company, awaiting popular Internet adoption.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said that the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs died that a complete copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This archive material, slightly reedited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview, which arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate deep interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and commercial strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points during the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Job's perfectionism comes to the surface, where it seems impatient because of Cringley's questions, pushing him to go faster on the issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the age of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of computer science.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there is something raw and inspiring in the Jobs we see here, the dreamer anxiously at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how they can and must be things.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way you do it."
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs brings in detail their efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Disappointed by the way in which the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of good cover, and then adjusted to a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that the commercial costs could be determined in detail.
On the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" that he himself built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long distance calls.
It has been written widely about the device, but Job's euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
Describes how he and Wozniak tried the box by using a public phone, making one call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half a dozen times and shouting through the public phone and returning a minute later to the public phone next door," Jobs says with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think there would ever have been Apple without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the US diplomat, the two broke into carcasses just before the Pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the telephone guide and called for spare parts to build a frequency counter.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job in Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and formed my vision of what was a company and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of HP employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first table computer ever made".
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the march.
Soon in his career, as he was dedicated to selling a handful of base plates, a customer asked him if he could mount the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of finished devices.
Later, while in Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they shouted to me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I crawled out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's rebirth, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of his market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, so what?"
You have the monopoly of the market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so these kinds of people who end up driving companies and people in charge of products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position is rotted because of people who do not have the notion of good products versus bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
Much is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to do - some things you can't do that make the electrons, the glass makes them, the robots do them, the factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything is reduced to taste - it is reduced to trying to expose you to the best that a human team has done, and then try to adapt those things to the things you are doing.
Picasso said the good artists copy, the great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed of stealing big ideas.
What made Macintosh big was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were by chance the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, it could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas eat with the rivals of the health care law while the court accepts the case
On the day that the Supreme Court met in private to consider the politically controversial question of whether they would accept the challenge to President Obama's health care law, two of his judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were given a dinner sponsored by the signature of lawyers who would present the case to the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met at a preliminary hearing to study carefully the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a demand from 26 states challenging the total reform of health care approved by Congress last year, a law that has been a war cry for conservative activists throughout the country.
The judges agreed to admit the application and, in fact, a historic claim of 5 and a half hours by March is expected, and the result will probably further disrupt the 2012 presidential career that will be in full swing at the time the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear before the court and will claim that the law must be discarded will probably be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during George W. Bush's government.
Clement's firm of lawyers, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles for many years.
Another signature that sponsored dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Affairs.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., who has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the dispute.
Dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was Mitch McConnell, the most important Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health care law.
Special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It's nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, it could be said that they would fall under the Code Canon 4C, which says, "A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related organizations and others, even if the judge cannot be a speaker, an honored guest, or appear on the programme of such an event."
However, the absolute proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as to a company with a huge financial interest, was sufficient to alarm ethics activists in the government.
"This striking gap of ethics and indifference to the code goes against the demands of several judges who judge the court by the same rules that apply to all federal judges," said Bob Edgar, President of Common Cause (Common Cause).
"The judges were hired in a collection of gala funds with lawyers who have pending cases before the court."
Its appearance and assistance in fund-raising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticisms that say they mix court activity too easily with the agenda driven by groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a leading conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Judge Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as Attorney General of the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were presented in the court of first instance.
His critics have pressured Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying that he was too involved in defending the law as to be impartial now.
