How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent lies and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment charges with several women; each party is accused of lying to the other.
The administrators of the State University of Pennsylvania have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that said a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolás Sarkozy was "picked up" with an open voice saying to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamín Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
Congressman for New York and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made the joke with his dissidents quickly refuted by irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with infringements in funding the campaign related to the covering of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one living it will ever forget the media circus directed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps are widely spread in school and university exams.
There have been cases in which teachers have given student reviews in order to be better viewed in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lies and deceit are acceptable.
How much deceit do we find?
Any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that the unknown lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to say: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of knowledge would be based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about the lie have been refuted.
The liars do look in the eye.
Not always tartamudean, bluffing, rustling or restful.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years exploring scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that outtroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-orientated" lies, while women say more lies "orientated towards others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently than those who are not married (but the lies they usually say are "enormous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty when you lie to him.
How do I know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called creating a basic line.
Helps provide benchmarks to measure later changes.
Watch the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
You better know if someone usually hits his foot all the time to avoid making unfair accusations when he sees his feet banging in the middle of the meeting.
Then seek misleading, verbal and non-verbal behaviour groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember its history, can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change their posture significantly or exhibit a "post-interview disorder" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all difficult questions have ended.
Questioners often falsely point out that the interview ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson kicked his foot to the bottom and used the past while he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distant language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand it."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
