Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official committee, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, composed of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will launch a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with its Mexican couple, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "proprietary for the exchange of information in all political affairs between the two nations", as the South American Presidency published on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when French representative Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
