Secretary Dionysio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air accident where the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake, lost his life, and seven more people
The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where the Government Secretary, Francisco Blake Mora, lost his life, and seven more people, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot could attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were the right conditions to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the terrain, the quotes had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so he had the necessary requirements to transport staff.
In addition, he said that in the research done in the impact area, there is no report of the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search there are reports that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The helicopter design was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary assured that it was a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, research can last several months, even a year.
For his part, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Staff operated at cruise speed and that this happened on an ascending soft terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the TBS holder Pérez Jácome listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical normability the flight was performed under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew should have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM provided adequate conditions for take-off, as the aircraft moved towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, they presented layers of low-level cloud.
Selected paths:
It is likely that under cloud conditions the crew has sought a less elevated area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of remaining parts of the aircraft in a small area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and side-by-side path.
The aircraft's residue dispersal pattern makes it possible to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under structural integrity conditions.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the disaster there is still no evidence in the remains of the ship of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that there may have been multiple contacts with the field.
During the field work pieces of the aircraft have been found at a elevation of 9 thousand 200 feet above the sea level, the ground has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was expected to disarrange throughout this journey.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a wider area than the site agreed, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact was presented in structural integrity conditions.
MSS announces protocol to find gene of obesity
Directs Social Security research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute for Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducts a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, known as the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol, which will enable markers associated with overweight.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry, Hospital de Specialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvesav) from the National Institute of Political Affairs (INP).
The investigation invites the population to participate, whether or not they are entitled to participate, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out for minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the sports unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Mexico West) and that since 8 October, the activity is carried out in the sports unit Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico East).
Once the objective of gathering 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
At the celebration of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he stated that the objective is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and hereditary history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He noted that Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, glucose levels determination, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys noted that in just six years, there was an increase of 77 percent in obesity in children and 47 percent in girls; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for finding the markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, obesity genetics translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the integral evaluation of children, which allows them to detect if they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the probability of metabolic alterations and even predisabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are told each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make in order to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic suffering: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, to stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and to use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugared beverages, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, burgers, et cetera) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would prevent berries
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemicals, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the floor were met, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 berries each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt floor is the right one, the berries could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
At his conference A technological opinion of the berries, dictated within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of berries.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weight ones, called asphalts, and others low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor their characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes broken, added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform, but that it is changing during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that most streets in Mexico City are covered by flexible flooring, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that makes up the folder, pointed, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread themselves very well on the floor.
In the case of modified asphalt, the chemical engineer was of the opinion.
On the asphalt folder, a last layer called a treadmill is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the way.
As part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the tread folder also needs to have the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground is wet, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a re-supply of all layers of the floor and therefore the formation of berries.
In the process of forming a bache, he said, the first to wear is the rolling film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not happen instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of berries and therefore the thickness of each of the layers of the floor must always be related to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid frequently forming berries.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow to repair berries easily and without needing to use high temperatures.
