This was the work of the calender that identified Alfonso Cano's corpse
A lophoscopist from Cali went on to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
Last November 4th, a lophoscopist of the Cali ITC passed on to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", through the collapsing of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the ITC section, that week was the turn of "availability" to Elias González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, the palms of his hands and feet.
The week of operation against Alfonso Cano alias to Elias warned him to wear clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he should identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to carry the decactillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the corpse was found, he did not recognize it because of his physical appearance, since he was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a peasant in the area, wearing glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galtonian lens, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Elias compared the fingerprints of the body to those of the card.
His eye failed: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, who was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the footprint
For a dictator of the Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Elias González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dictyloscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can become a key to solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals present false ballots or have no papers.
We take fingerprints and search them in the database.
The investigator reported that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to remove a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the footprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
The fingerprints may also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
Recently they found a dead man with liquor bottles around him.
By means of the investigation it was determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a trace in the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that it was the killer, it does place it in the scene of the crime.
One ITC dictivist explained that in the objects "the footprints are taken out with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that touches becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective quota is made.
The "indignant" challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters flocked to Zuccotti square to camp.
A large part heeded the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
The members of the Occupa Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities this Tuesday by trying to enter again, under the protection of a judicial order, into Manhattan Square from where they were evicted in the morning and by trying to occupy another park of the Great Manzana.
Hundreds of protesters flocked to Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a judicial order that allows the "indignant" to camp again in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court doesn't allow us to camp again in the square, we're going to install somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sittings and demonstrations," said one of the spokespersons of the "Occupa Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the "indignant" to the eviction of his camp personally dictated by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the place and allowed protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the "indignant" proceeded to the occupation of a new park located in the confluence of the central Canal Street and the Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and property of the parish of Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to take the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the specific figure, while he assured Ephe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization claims that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders had already been moved to support members of the movement and had tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zucccotti Square - which is a private property facility - remains closed pending the holding of a judicial hearing scheduled for this same Tuesday, where the legality of the evacuation of this morning must be analysed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and distributed copies of that order at this time and even handed them over to the agents guarding the plaza, which caused "some small clashes," Bray pointed out, who denounced that some officers had hit the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evicting the members of Occupa Wall Street or applying "laws which were published after the occupation began or from prohibiting protesters from entering the park again with shops or other properties they used earlier".
Mayor Bloomberg pointed out to the press that because of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and to the protesters, who warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to reinstall themselves with tents and sleeping bags.
The director personally defended the eviction carried out in the early morning of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which approximately 200 arrests took place and which was decided because the protesters were "violent of the law".
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate laws and, in some cases, to harm other people", as "some businesses had received threats" and neighbors feared "for their quality of life".
"The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests of American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of "lacking respect for freedom of expression".
The leaders of "Occupa Wall Street" also indicated that they plan to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions, to commemorate the two months during the protests, which began on September 17.
