Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of falls that started in March.
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, even though the devastating earthquake that has taken place in a nuclear crisis has been the worst disaster the country has had since World War II.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo accounted for material losses in $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seemed to have diminished.
After three consecutive trimesters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to pass page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at annual rate.
The record in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the rebound of the purchase of machinery to restore areas devastated by seism and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, the companies increased their investments by 1.1%, as compared to the decrease of 0.9% in capital expenditure from January to March, the first retreat after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real revolution of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that invites the use of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructures, to use gaps to grow from scratch.
Japan has aroused, above all, the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60 per cent of Japanese GDP.
This variable rose by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, trips and leisure activities.
The Shark's Stigma
Tokyo has been entrusted to the internal market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "valuable shelter" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the turbulent US forecasts, a privilege that weighs as a loss on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious downturn for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, focused their weak results between July and September on the contribution of yen.
As long as the markets remain under siege to the peripheral countries of the EU, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
"We must be aware of the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand's floods and the rapid appreciation of yen," said the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And, indeed, prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) stated that most member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy highlighted that the main powers are being slowed down.
As it dropped four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 August.
