Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With the peripheral risk premiums fired and the uncertainty reinstalled in the parks, Greece continues to be entangled in the maze leading to the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek transitional Government is more imposed by the demands of Brussels than by a genuine conviction of the political forces begins to be confirmed with facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there was no alternative for structural reforms and that the one-hundred-day period agreed on in his designation might be short to apply them, the leader of the Conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support further austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections by the scheduled date on 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the 26 October summit," said Papadimos in opening yesterday a parliamentary debate which will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new executive.
A package with 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the staff disciplinary code and further measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message leaves no doubt about his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the transitional government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything else."
The conservative leader was a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the agencies that must unlock the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and made it clear that he will not give his visa to any letter of compromise to comply with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still shocked by the impact caused by the order of the Papandreu referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not unlock the aid if the new government and the leaders of the major Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity and as soon as possible".
The spokesperson for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the Troika inspectors will return "to Athens very soon" to discuss with the new government "what is needed to pay the sixth instalment" of 8,000 million, although there is no definitive date.
