As in other cases, the effects of the announcement appear to be slightly disproportionate to the reality of the low-labour fraud.
In fact, since 2002, there has been constant follow-up to this issue and a number of political offensives have been launched, which have normally produced fruit.
The French are only inferring in the rest of Europe.
Let us look at the national figures in the first place.
According to the French Institute for Social Security (CNAM), more than 237 million euros were paid in employment benefits in 2006.
According to the French Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, low-income subsidies accounted for 5 per cent of health expenditure in 2008.
Of this amount, 46 per cent corresponds to maternity and occupational accidents, while 54 per cent is related to sickness benefits, amounting to EUR 6,200 million.
Therefore, 2.5 per cent of health expenditure.
