An average that undoubtedly hides deviations: another survey, published in 2007 by Syrian professional management Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed claimed that they had not taken a single day off for illness.
Another study, in this case of Sickness Insurance, indicates that in 2010 37% of disease casualties were less than 8 days, 22% between 8 and 14 days, 15% between 15 days and 1 month, 15% between one and three months and 11% were longer.
If we compare them with our European neighbours, French workers are no more likely than in other areas to take sick leave.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers indicated that, between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate of work (both for health and other reasons) in France ranged from 10 per cent to 11 per cent, compared to 20 per cent and 28 per cent in Denmark, 15 per cent in the United Kingdom or 16 per cent to 18 per cent in the Netherlands.
Low-disease fraud is not particularly significant compared to undeclared work.
Fraud has a fairly limited scope.
