In 2008, of 1.5 million inspections, CNAM found, in 13 per cent of the 285,000 cases, that short-term reductions were "unjustified or too long", i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of casualties of more than 45 days, subject to systematic inspections, it was considered that 11 per cent of the cases were "adequately adapted or unjustified; a figure starting at a total of 1.2 million was considered to be 132,000.
Consequently, a total of 169,000 "unjustified" cases were reached among several million workers who took a sick leave.
No doubt, an insignificant figure compared, for example, to work in black.
According to the Member of the UMP Dominique Tian, the author of a report on this issue in June, this practice would represent tax revenue losses of between 9,000 and 15,000 million euros per year, that is, more than the total cost of lower subsidies and, no doubt, considerably more than fraud in the latter area.
