An expert committee asserts that euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized
Canadians are living in denial of death, as indicated in the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not only in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they wish to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts in various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so that assisted suicide and euthanasia are permitted, when the patient raises such an option and has been tried to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada occupies the tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the subject of death."
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, as indicated by the experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the fact that most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Together, the highest rate in this sense is registered by Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive subject of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the federal government's position, which has already stated that they do not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or are not criminal offences, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with non-compliant persons or that they have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal."
