The North Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, over 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the North Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Similarly, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, it will reach an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas each year to Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km to communicate the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be concluded at the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55,000 million cubic metres of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk about the possibility of building a third tube through the same route.
For Gazprom, the finalization in time of this enormous work presents air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had firmly opposed the project.
In fact, North Stream is going to allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land transit by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening it by closing access to markets in Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe of energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to win its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This pipeline is a component of our association with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically," said François Fillon during the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom's directors, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement coated steel to protect it against the anchorages of the ships.
It is supported at the bottom of the sea, an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid mines that date from the Second World War.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, by caution," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream society.
It was also necessary to stress the protection measures of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but project managers gave up on it when they saw that Swedes were not prepared to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently in the sea off their shores.
"In case we fail, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In case of escape, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders find it unlikely that there will be a leak, since they have planned joints which, according to forecasts, will have an escape every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a submarine robot, dragged by a vessel, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates through the inside of the pipeline.
In the form of a pure, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without need of any repair.
Gas circulation is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bar and, at the exit of 100 bar.
Five companies have united their forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
Germany joined E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all gas transport capacities.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Funding for gas pipeline construction has ended by 30% with the contribution of shareholders and by 70% with bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.400 million for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone takes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
A valve, with 4.5 meters of height, forms the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million an hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, brand name card.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an adventure air, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current aspect were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based on Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design notes to the market, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, by then consulting the company, took care of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (top leather), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, inter alia, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he was successful.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, up to 12.7 million units sold.
Far has remained the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, as the notebook attracts both business men and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookshops, from Fnac to the small shops of the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with Moleskine's development: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Enjoying success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer backgrounds... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for employment.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled starts today.
Despite a determined public policy, applied since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Discouragement?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high as the average.
"However, there's still a lot to do."
It should be mentioned that disabled persons continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (an average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished the bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent on average.
That is, there are many issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased from 2007 to 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Law which increased contributions has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
